>Rather than writing out the sound of the sword being sheathed you could say "the sword returned to its scabbard with a sound of water pouring heated metal" Or "the sword was sheathed with a soft click as hilt met scabbard."

I don't really like colorful descriptions like this. They go overboard and don't really add anything to the story. I think it's a lot better if you instead try to connect descriptions to the scene and characters.

I haven't read much of your story, but I want to ad-lib the sound idea a little. I'd write something like this:


The thrust overpowered Garek, pushing him backward onto the ground. Above him came the familiar sound of his opponent's sword scraping into its scabbard. It's a sound he hated. It's the sound of defeat.


Readers are good at filling your world with their own imagination. You can't describe everything, so descriptions should direct readers to what you think matters. Use them to set up things that you plan to pay off later. Use them to tell the reader something new about your setting or characters. Use them as if they're commentary from your characters. Character commentary is great because each character should have a different perspective.

Don't worry too much about it though. Keep trying to move forward while you grow rather than staying in the same place overly focusing on perfection.
